This was a very good show.  Don't listen to the negative reviews!  It was a moving story of a man who had his priorities all wrong and was headed in the wrong direction.  Owen suffered from a great deal of loneliness, using alcohol and the party life to fill in for what was missing- human connection.  After a fall caused him to break an arm and sit in the ED waiting room for hours, he began to examine what he was doing wrong- especially in regard to his young son.  It was a great analogy to see how as the seasons of the year changed, so did Owen.  He stopped drinking, took responsibility for himself and became an adult that his son and family could be proud of.  He really stepped up in taking care of his neighbor Todd and his sister.  I loved how he made a new family for himself from close friends, a cousin, and his son- a great lesson in the truth that family is who is close to you, blood is not necessary.  Positive story that moves at a good pace to keep you interested- a real example of growth that makes one evaluate your own life to see what changes could be made.  Highly Recommend.

I like character movies and have patience for a slower pace--as long as the movie doesn't trail off into some fake fairytale or grim house of horrors. This quiet movie takes some surprising turns, but it always feels real. The characters make sense, and what happens is a natural outcome of who they are--mixed in with just the right amount of hope and love. So glad I watched the trailer (I'd never heard of this film) and gave it a chance. The voiceover adds poignancy without ever turning saccharine. Like the hairdresser, I hate fake sweetness. No worries about that in this movie. Highly recommend.

It's kind of a coming of age film in which a moy becomes a man, father, friend etc. The acting was great on everyone's part, good script and production, all the way through, very humble regular guy finds his way, and people around him do too. I love this movie.  It's very real to life in that it shows real problems real people face and the consequences, some hard, some sad and some happy.  It shows us that no matter what we face in life, we can change our surroundings and we can change ourselves.  Loneliness can be a tough feeling to overcome as this movie shows, but it also shows that loneliness can be overcome.  The ties of family are strong here, whether it be blood family or friends that become family.  This movie brought tears of sadness and tears of happiness.  There are a lot of good lines in this movie with a lot of meaning.  I love that it has a good happy ending.  I will definitely recommend this movie to others.

Surprisingly good movie. Low key and slow paced with realistic emotional reactions.  The antihero of the film is a drunken low achiever who rather than the instant life changing experience goes through a gradual awakening of what his life can be if he straightens himself up. It was very rewarding to see how this flawed man's character developed into a rounded person who cared for and took care of those he loves.

It's a slice of life love story with an element of redemption, but manages to stay the right side of corny and cliche at all times. It's not earth shattering amazing, but this is about real people making real mistakes and real choices in their lives. There is the right balance of humour and sentiment, so I would say it's well written and I was surprised by how much I enjoyed watching it.

I really did enjoy this movie. You could see the development of not just the lead character played by Bryan Greenberg, but in other characters in the story. The changes he makes, and the impact of those changes on others as well, is the crux of the story. Family is important to me, and this movie illustrates that concept, as well as the idea that family encompasses more than those related to us by blood; it includes those we choose to define as our family. I think alcoholism is probably a little harder to kick than as portrayed in the movie, but is my only critique.

More like 3.5 stars but I don't get all the 5 star reviews.  An aimless guy with an ex-wife and a dysfunctional family tries to get his life together.  The acting was ok for this low budget film and I found myself rooting for this guy to overcome his troubles.  The lesson: actions have consequences.  It's not rated but there are a number of F-bombs, no nudity but a couple of sex scenes.
This is one of those independent film gems that makes searching independent films so worth while.  A great story with some lovable characters.  Beautifully done.

I'm very picky when it comes to choosing a movie, I remember countless times standing around the video store, "remember those?," for 45 minutes before settling on a movie.  "A Year and Change" was one of 5 films I was contemplating downloading to my iPad and I'm glad it made the cut.  Very well written and directed with solid acting.  The filmmaker established the characters very early on and you were invested in their lives.  Not only that, but it gets you thinking about your own life.  Please add more "indy" type films to Amazon, or fund your own!  Highly recommend.
